# Difference Between Function Declaration, Function Expression, and Arrow Function

| Feature             | Function Declaration | Function Expression | Arrow Function           |
| ------------------- | -------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Syntax              | Traditional          | Stored in Variable  | Shortest                 |
| Hoisting            | Yes                  | No                  | No                       |
| Function Name       | Required             | Optional            | Usually Anonymous        |
| Own `this`          | Yes                  | Yes                 | No                       |
| Constructor Support | Yes                  | Yes                 | No                       |
| Readability         | High                 | Medium              | High for Short Functions |

## Summary

Functions are reusable blocks of code that help organize and simplify JavaScript programs. Function Declarations are traditional and hoisted, making 
them suitable for reusable logic. Function Expressions provide flexibility by treating functions as values and are commonly used in callbacks. Arrow
Functions offer a concise syntax and lexical `this` binding, making them popular in modern JavaScript development. Understanding all three types of 
functions is essential for writing efficient, maintainable, and professional JavaScript code.
